        <div class="text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-red-brand mb-2">Compliance · April 2026 · 10 min read</div>
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Orlando, FL: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Orlando, FL, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Orlando Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the Florida Fire Prevention Code (NFPA 1) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Orlando Fire Extinguisher Inspection Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Orlando enforces the Florida Fire Prevention Code (NFPA 1), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Four inspection intervals apply to every commercial extinguisher.</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Orlando's tourism and hospitality economy creates fire extinguisher compliance demands at exceptional scale. International Drive's hotel and resort corridor, the theme park support facilities, convention centers, and the dense restaurant and entertainment zone around I-Drive all require comprehensive fire extinguisher coverage and annual inspection compliance. Florida's high humidity and heat also accelerate dry chemical agent caking in extinguisher cylinders — units in outdoor or high-humidity locations should be inspected more frequently.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by your own trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, the tamper seal is intact, and the pull pin is in place. Document every monthly check. In the event of a fire incident or an enforcement action, the absence of monthly records significantly increases your liability exposure.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed fire protection technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle integrity, and overall unit condition — then attaches a dated service tag. Florida is unique in that it enforces NFPA 1 (not the IFC) as its statewide fire prevention code. Fire extinguisher service contractors in Florida must be licensed under Chapter 633, Florida Statutes, administered by the Florida Division of State Fire Marshal (850-413-3140). Verify your service provider holds a current Florida license before scheduling service. Any unit that fails must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation that external inspections miss. This typically includes a complete recharge. Missing the 6-year exam is a frequently cited violation during Orlando Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>

        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must undergo hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned. After passing, units are recharged and marked with the new test date. Plan for some units to require replacement at the 12-year mark — budget accordingly.</p>

