        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often do fire extinguishers need to be inspected in Orlando, FL?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">In Orlando, FL, fire extinguishers require monthly visual inspections (performed by building staff), annual professional inspections by a licensed technician, 6-year internal examinations, and 12-year hydrostatic testing per NFPA 10 and the Florida Fire Prevention Code (NFPA 1).</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does a fire extinguisher inspection cost in Orlando, FL?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Annual fire extinguisher inspections in the Orlando metro typically cost $15–$38 per unit. 6-year internal examinations run $26–$55 per unit. 12-year hydrostatic testing costs $32–$70 per unit. Volume discounts are available for properties with 20 or more extinguishers.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who can inspect fire extinguishers in Orlando, FL?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Monthly visual checks can be performed by trained building staff. Annual inspections, 6-year internals, and 12-year hydrostatic tests must be performed by a licensed fire protection technician. Florida is unique in that it enforces NFPA 1 (not the IFC) as its statewide fire prevention code. Fire extinguisher service contractors in Florida must be licensed under Chapter 633, Florida Statutes, administered by the Florida Division of State Fire Marshal (850-413-3140). Verify your service provider holds a current Florida license before scheduling service.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What are the penalties for fire extinguisher violations in Orlando?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The Orlando Fire Department issues notices of violation for fire extinguisher deficiencies with correction periods. Uncorrected violations can result in escalating fines. Serious life-safety deficiencies — missing extinguishers, expired tags in high-occupancy areas — face accelerated enforcement timelines.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does Orlando require fire extinguishers in all commercial buildings?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. The Florida Fire Prevention Code (NFPA 1) requires portable fire extinguishers in all commercial, industrial, and multi-family residential buildings in Orlando. Type, size, and placement depend on occupancy classification and hazard level as defined by NFPA 10.</p></div></div>

